<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,1257]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,258,284]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wang et Zheng" authorityYear="1995" box="[662,821,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Ripeacma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fopingensis">
<emphasis box="[662,821,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">R. fopingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Xu &amp; Wang, 2022" authorityName="Xu &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[876,1060,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Ripeacma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediprocessa" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[876,1060,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">R. mediprocessa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1067,1131,259,285]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1067,1131,259,285]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in male genitalia. It can be distinguished by the stout uncus without lateral lobes, the semicircular gnathos, and the aedeagus trilobed distally. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wang et Zheng" authorityYear="1995" box="[183,343,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Ripeacma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fopingensis">
<emphasis box="[183,343,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">R. fopingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the slender uncus has a rounded setose lobe laterally, the gnathos is roughly X-shaped, and the aedeagus has two pointed lobes distally. For differences between 
<taxonomicName authority="Xu &amp; Wang, 2022" authorityName="Xu &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[884,1014,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Ripeacma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trilobata" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[884,1014,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">R. trilobata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1021,1084,367,393]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1021,1084,367,393]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Xu &amp; Wang, 2022" authorityName="Xu &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[1139,1323,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Oecophoridae" genus="Ripeacma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediprocessa" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1139,1323,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">R. mediprocessa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1330,1394,367,393]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1330,1394,367,393]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
see diagnosis under the latter species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="537" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,1257]" box="[199,838,438,465]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,438,464]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Description.</emphasis>
Adult (
<figureCitation box="[429,513,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–14" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1394,1418]" captionTargetBox="[199,1384,186,1358]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[170,1417,178,1373]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 9–14. Adults of Ripeacma spp. 9, R. stigmosa sp. nov.; 10, R. acerba sp. nov.; 11, R. ellipsoidea sp. nov.; 12, R. hamatispina sp. nov.; 13, R. mediprocessa sp. nov.; 14, R. trilobata sp. nov., paratype, ♀. All holotypes and males, except paratype and female for R. trilobata. Scales = 1.00 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6911457" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6911457/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 10.0 − 13.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,1257]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis box="[199,260,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Head</emphasis>
with frons yellowish white, vertex brown. Labial palpus pale yellow, second palpomere black distally; third palpomere in female black except yellow at apex. Antenna black on dorsal surface; scape yellow and flagellum brown on ventral surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,1257]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis box="[199,280,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Thorax</emphasis>
and tegula dark brown. Forewing dark brown; costal spot yellow, sub-triangular, placed at distal 1/5; discal, discocellular and plical stigmata black, edged with a whitish yellow stripe or a few whitish yellow scales; fringe black. Hindwing dark grey; fringe greyish brown, with a whitish yellow basal line. Legs yellow; on dorsal surface, femur and tibia of foreleg dark brown, tibia of midleg black, with a yellow stripe at middle, tarsi of fore- and midlegs black at middle of first tarsomere and at base of second tarsomere as well as on entire third and fourth tarsomeres; on outer surface, tibia of hindleg black, tarsus black at middle of first tarsomere and at base of other tarsomeres.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,1257]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis box="[199,365,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[382,468,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–26" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1719,1743]" captionTargetBox="[173,1401,191,1686]" captionTargetId="figure-19@11.[173,1413,181,1695]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 21–26. Male genitalia of Ripeacma spp. 21, R. stigmosa sp. nov., slide No. LiSR16228; 22, R. acerba sp. nov., slide No. LiSR17013; 23, R. ellipsoidea sp. nov., slide No. LiSR16270; 24, R. hamatispina sp. nov., slide No. LiSR16284; 25, R. mediprocessa sp. nov., slide No. XZX20421; 26, R. trilobata sp. nov., slide No. XZX20424. All holotypes. Scales = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6911463" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6911463/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Uncus relatively stout, broad at base, narrowed to basal 1/3, subparallel to truncate apex. Gnathos ring-like. Valva narrowed at base, gradually widened to basal 1/3, subparallel from basal 1/3 to obtusely rounded apex; costa banded, reaching middle length of costal margin; transtilla lobes uniformly banded, extending obliquely dorsad, joined mesially by membrane; sacculus slightly shorter than 1/3 length of valva, subtriangular, narrowed from wide base to apex, with a small apical spine hooked dorsad. Saccus triangular, apex obtusely rounded. Juxta narrowly banded; lateral arm slender, curved. Aedeagus longer than 2/3 length of valva, almost tubular, trilobed distally: first divided into two lobes from middle, one lobe furcate distally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,1257]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis box="[199,393,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[411,498,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 27–32" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1908,1932]" captionTargetBox="[199,1391,198,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-26@12.[180,1408,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 27–32. Female genitalia of Ripeacma spp. 27, R. anisopenis sp. nov., slide No. LiSR16278; 28, R. bitriangulata sp. nov., slide No. LiSR16287; 29, R. magnimaculata sp. nov., slide No. XZX20415; 30, R. hamatispina sp. nov., slide No. LiSR16299; 31, R. mediprocessa sp. nov., slide No. XZX20154; 32, R. trilobata sp. nov., slide No. XZX20098. All paratypes. Scales = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6911465" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6911465/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
). Apophyses anteriores about half length of apophyses posteriores. Eighth sternal plate relatively narrow. Antrum slightly widened posteriorly. Ductus bursae membranous, not distinctly separated from corpus bursae. Corpus bursae elongate elliptical, without signum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,645,1194,1221]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,1257]" box="[199,645,1194,1221]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1194,1220]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,426,1195,1221]" name="China" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[441,517,1195,1221]" country="China" name="Fujian" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Fujian</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[528,633,1195,1221]" country="China" name="Zhejiang" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Zhejiang</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1418,1231,1257]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,1257]" box="[199,1418,1231,1257]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1231,1257]" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[762,798,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">tri-</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[853,935,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="537">lobatus</emphasis>
, referring to the distally trilobed aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
